<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-10-01T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-10-01T23:00:00-05:00" n="1044" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1044">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/2167: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Butrick</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-10-02T13:00:00+09:00">October 2, 1940—1
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received October 3—8:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1018. Certain apprehensive Americans here inquire [about] evacuation,
                                fearing internment [in] event [of] war. Point out [that] our
                                Emergency Committee, though active, cannot cope with such situation.
                                United States shipping [in] Far East inadequate, vessels [from]
                                Shanghai [to] home practically booked [to] end year.</p>
                            <p>Sent to the Department, repeated to Peiping, Chungking.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Butrick</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>